<h2>How to Set Up AI Agents on Your WordPress Site &#123;#chapter-5&#125;</h2>
<p>Setup depends on whether you use WordPress.com or self-hosted WordPress.org. Here is a step-by-step breakdown for both.</p>
<h3>WordPress.com Setup (5 Minutes)</h3>
<ul>
<li>[ ] Log in to your WordPress.com account</li>
<li>[ ] Go to Account Settings and find MCP Configuration</li>
<li>[ ] Enable MCP access and select which operations to allow</li>
<li>[ ] Open your AI agent (Claude, ChatGPT, or another MCP-compatible tool)</li>
<li>[ ] Connect to your WordPress.com site using the MCP endpoint</li>
<li>[ ] Test with a simple command: "Show me my 5 most recent posts"</li>
<li>[ ] Verify the agent can read your content before enabling write operations</li>
</ul>
<p>Every change defaults to draft status. You must explicitly enable auto-publishing if you want it.</p>
<h3>WordPress.org Setup (15-30 Minutes)</h3>
<p>Self-hosted sites require a plugin to expose MCP capabilities.</p>
<ul>
<li>[ ] Install the AI Engine plugin from the WordPress plugin directory</li>
<li>[ ] Activate MCP Server mode in the plugin settings</li>
<li>[ ] Configure API authentication (REST API key or application password)</li>
<li>[ ] Set permission levels for the agent connection</li>
<li>[ ] Connect your AI agent using the site URL and API credentials</li>
<li>[ ] Test read operations first, then enable write operations</li>
<li>[ ] Set up approval workflows if multiple team members manage content</li>
</ul>
<h3>Configuration Best Practices</h3>
<p><strong>Start with read-only access.</strong> Let the agent analyze your site for a few days before granting write permissions. This builds your confidence in its understanding of your content.</p>
<p><strong>Use draft mode for the first 2 weeks.</strong> Review every piece of content the agent creates. Patterns emerge quickly. You will spot recurring issues to address in your prompt instructions.</p>
<p><strong>Create an agent-specific WordPress user.</strong> Do not connect the agent to your admin account. Create a dedicated user with editor or author permissions. This keeps your Activity Log clean and limits blast radius if something goes wrong.</p>
