<h3>When to Use Each</h3>
<p><strong>Use plugins</strong> for in-editor assistance while you write. Grammar checking, readability scoring, and SEO analysis work well as plugins.</p>
<p><strong>Use agents</strong> for production workflows. Content calendars, bulk publishing, metadata cleanup, and content refreshing are agent territory.</p>
<p>The best WordPress content operations use both. Plugins help you write better. Agents help you publish more. For teams exploring <a href="/blog/ai-marketing-automation/">AI marketing automation</a>, agents are the natural next step.</p>
<h2>Quality Control and Human Oversight &#123;#chapter-7&#125;</h2>
<p>AI agents produce content fast. Speed without quality control creates a different kind of problem. Here is how to keep standards high while publishing at scale.</p>
<h3>The Approval Layer</h3>
<p>WordPress.com requires explicit approval for every agent action. Use this feature. Do not enable auto-publishing until you have reviewed at least 50 agent-generated posts and confirmed consistent quality.</p>
<p>Every agent action should follow this loop:</p>
<ol>
<li>Agent proposes the action</li>
<li>Human reviews the proposal</li>
<li>Agent executes after approval</li>
<li>Human spot-checks the published result</li>
</ol>
<h3>Content Quality Checklist</h3>
<p>Run this checklist on every AI-generated post before publishing:</p>
<ul>
<li>[ ] Factual claims are verified with source links</li>
<li>[ ] Statistics include publication dates (reject anything older than 18 months)</li>
<li>[ ] No hallucinated brand names, products, or URLs</li>
<li>[ ] Tone matches your existing published content</li>
<li>[ ] Internal links point to real pages on your site</li>
<li>[ ] Meta description includes the target keyword</li>
<li>[ ] Alt text exists on every image</li>
<li>[ ] Post length meets your minimum word count standard</li>
</ul>
<h3>The Hallucination Problem</h3>
<p><a href="https://wpmayor.com/wordpress-ai-statistics/">79% of professionals</a> express concern about AI spreading misinformation. This concern is valid. AI agents can present fabricated data as fact.</p>
<p>The fix is a verification step. Never publish statistics, quotes, or specific claims without confirming the source. Build this into your workflow as a non-negotiable gate.</p>
<h3>Editing Cadence</h3>
<p>Review 100% of agent content in month 1. Move to 50% spot-checks in month 2. By month 3, review 25% if quality remains consistent. Never drop below 10% review rates, even with a proven agent setup.</p>
<p>For guidance on making AI-generated content sound natural, read our guide on how to <a href="/blog/humanize-ai-content/">humanize AI content</a>.</p>
